TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bootstrap Testing in Nonlinear Models
AU  - Davidson, Russell
AU  - MacKinnon, James G.
Y1  - 1999/05/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.00026
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 487
EP  - 508
VL  - 40
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.00026
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Bootstrap testing of nonlinear models normally requires at least one nonlinear estimation for every bootstrap sample. We show how to reduce computational costs by performing only a fixed, small number of Newton or quasi-Newton steps for each bootstrap sample. The number of steps is smaller for likelihood ratio tests than for other types of classical tests and smaller for Newton's method than for quasi-Newton methods. The suggested procedures are applied to tests of slope coefficients in the tobit model and to tests of common factor restrictions. In both cases, bootstrap tests work well, and very few steps are needed.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Generalized Moments Estimator for the Autoregressive Parameter in a Spatial Model
AU  - Kelejian, Harry H.
AU  - Prucha, Ingmar R.
Y1  - 1999/05/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.00027
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 509
EP  - 533
VL  - 40
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-2354.00027
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper is concerned with the estimation of the autoregressive parameter in a widely considered spatial autocorrelation model. The typical estimator for this parameter considered in the literature is the (quasi) maximum likelihood estimator corresponding to a normal density. However, as discussed in this paper, the (quasi) maximum likelihood estimator may not be computationally feasible in many cases involving moderate- or large-sized samples. In this paper we suggest a generalized moments estimator that is computationally simple irrespective of the sample size. We provide results concerning the large and small sample properties of this estimator.
ER  - 
